-- South African Corn Prices Rise, Following an Advance in Chicago Trading
-- Mkhululi Mancotywa
-- 2010-06-14T07:55:13Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-14/south-african-corn-prices-rise-following-an-advance-in-chicago-trading.html

          
          
             Corn in South Africa, the largest
producer of the grain on the continent, gained after prices rose
in the U.S., which competes for African export markets.  
 Corn futures for December delivery rose 0.1 percent to
$3.715 a bushel on the Chicago Board of Trade at 8:42 a.m.
London time, the fifth consecutive gain.  
 White corn for July delivery, the most active contract on
the South African Futures Exchange, climbed 11 rand, or 1
percent, to 1,079 rand ($140) a metric ton in Johannesburg. Meal
made from the grain is the country’s staple food.  
 Yellow corn for July delivery rose 7 rand, or 0.6 percent,
to 1,121 rand a ton. The grain is used mainly as animal feed in
South Africa. The U.S. and Argentina are the biggest corn
exporters.  
 Wheat for July delivery was unchanged at 2,297 rand a ton.
Morocco, Egypt and Algeria are Africa’s largest wheat growers.  
 The gains or losses for the most active contracts of the
following crops today were as follows. All prices are in rand
and the crops are sold per ton:  

 
            Today’s Price   Previous Close   % Change
Sunflowers       3,415          3,415           0.0
Soybeans         2,560          2,537          +0.9
Sorghum          1,400          1,400           0.0
 
